Claims Claims 1. RFID transponder comprising a coding and modulation unit (CMU) designed to generate a transmission signal (S_t) by modulating an oscillator signal (S_o) with an encoded bit signal (S_e) , the oscillator signal (S_o) having an oscillator frequency, wherein during a transmission period, the encoded bit signal (S_e) has, during a first time segment (Tl) of the transmission period, a first logic level and, during a second time segment (T2) of the transmission period, a second logic level being different from the first logic level; and the transmission signal (S_t) - comprises, within the first time segment (Tl), a first signal pulse (PI) having the oscillator frequency and a first phase depending on the first logic level; - comprises, within the second time segment (T2), a second signal pulse (P2) having the oscillator frequency and a second phase depending on the second logic level and being shifted with respect to the first phase by a predefined phase difference; and - is paused for a pause period (TP) between the first and the second signal pulse (PI, P2), the pause period (TP) being shorter than a mean value of a period of the first time segment (Tl) and a period of the second time segment (T2 ) . 2. RFID transponder according to claim 1 , wherein the coding and modulation unit (CMU) is designed to generate the encoded bit signal (S_e) based on a data bit signal (S_d) , wherein the data bit signal (S_d) represents data to be transmitted by the RFID transponder to a reading device. 3. RFID transponder according to claim 2, wherein, for generating the encoded bit signal (S_e) , the coding and modulation unit (CMU) is designed to apply a predefined coding algorithm and/or to apply a Manchester coding algorithm, to the data bit signal (S_d) . 4. RFID transponder according to one of claims 2 or 3, wherein the coding and modulation unit (CMU) is designed to generate the encoded bit signal (S_e) based on the data bit signal (S_e) and on a subcarrier signal, wherein the subcarrier signal is a binary clock signal with a subcarrier frequency being smaller than the oscillator frequency. 5. RFID transponder according to claim 4, wherein the encoded bit signal (S_e) corresponds to the subcarrier signal with a phase depending on a logic level of the data bit signal (S_d) . 6. RFID transponder according to one of claims 1 to 5, wherein the encoded bit signal (S_e) is generated to switch its value from the first logic level to the second logic level exactly once during the transmission period. 7. RFID transponder according to one of claims 1 to 6, wherein the transmission period has a length corresponding to a total cycle number multiplied with a cycle period depending on the oscillator frequency; the first signal pulse (PI) comprises a first cycle number of cycles, each having a length given by the cycle period; the second signal pulse (P2) comprises a second cycle number of cycles, each having a length given by the cycle period; 

 the pause period (TP) has a length corresponding to a pause cycle number multiplied with the cycle period; the total cycle number is equal to a sum of the first, the second and the pause cycle number; and - each of the first, the second and the pause cycle number is equal to or smaller than one half of the total cycle number . 8. RFID transponder according to one of claims 1 to 7, further comprising an antenna system (A) and a front end circuitry (FE) connected to the antenna system (A) and configured to generate, during the pause period (TP) , a reader signal (S_r) based on a radio-frequency field detected by the antenna system (A) ; and a phase-locked loop circuit (PLL) designed to generate the oscillator signal (S_o) and to synchronize the oscillator signal (S_o) and the reader signal (S_r) during a lock period within the pause period (TP) . 9. RFID transponder according to claim 8, wherein the phase- locked loop circuit (PLL) is designed to synchronize the oscillator signal (S_o) and the reader signal (S_r) by ensuring a predefined constant phase relation between the oscillator signal (S_o) and the reader signal (S_r) during the lock period. 10. RFID transponder according to one of claims 8 or 9, wherein the phase-locked loop circuit (PLL) is designed to operate in an unlocked mode at times outside of the lock period, wherein the phase-locked loop circuit does not synchronize the oscillator signal (S_o) and the reader signal (S r) when operating in the unlocked mode. 11. RFID transponder according to one of claims 8 to 10, further comprising a damping circuitry (DMP) configured to attenuate the antenna system (A) at least during a part of the pause period (TP) . 12. RFID transponder according to claim 11, wherein the damping circuitry (DMP) is configured to attenuate the antenna system (A) during an attenuation period within the pause period (TP) , wherein the attenuation period precedes the lock period. 13. RFID transponder according to one of claims 1 to 12, wherein the pause period (TP) begins before the first time segment (Tl) has ended and the pause period (TP) ends after the second time segment (T2) has begun. 14. RFID transponder according to one of claims 1 to 13, wherein the pause period (TP) is shorter than or equal to a period of the first signal pulse (Tl) and the pause period (TP) is shorter than or equal to a period of the second signal pulse (T2) . 15. RFID transponder according to one of claims 1 to 14, wherein a transmission frame comprises a plurality of transmission periods including the transmission period; the encoded bit signal (S_e) and the transmission signal (S_t) are generated in a periodic manner at least during the plurality of transmission periods; during each of the transmission periods the encoded bit signal (S_e) has during a respective first time segment 

 (Tl) the first logic level and during a respective second time segment (T2) the second logic level; and during each of the transmission periods, the transmission signal (S_t) - comprises, within the respective first time segment (Tl), a respective first signal pulse (PI) having the oscillator frequency and the first phase; - comprises, within the respective second time segment (T2), a respective second signal pulse (P2) having the oscillator frequency and the second phase; and - is paused for a respective pause period (TP) between the respective first and the respective second signal pulse (PI, P2), the respective pause period (TP) being shorter than a mean value of a period of the respective first time segment (Tl) and a period of the respective second time segment (T2) . 16. Method for data transmission by means of RFID technology, the method comprising - generating a transmission signal (S_rt) by modulating an oscillator signal (S_o) with an encoded bit signal (S_e) , the oscillator signal (S_o) having an oscillator frequency, wherein during a transmission period, the encoded bit signal (S_e) has, during a first time segment (Tl) of the transmission period, a first logic level and, during a second time segment (T2) of the transmission period, a second logic level being different from the first logic level; and the transmission signal (S_t) - comprises, within the first time segment (Tl), a first signal pulse (PI) having the oscillator frequency and a first phase depending on the first logic level; 

 comprises, within the second time segment (T2), a second signal pulse (P2) having the oscillator frequency and a second phase depending on the second logic level and being shifted with respect to the first phase predefined phase difference; is paused for a pause period (TP) between the first and the second signal pulse (PI, P2), the pause period (TP) being shorter than a mean value of a period of the first time segment (Tl) and a period of the second time segment (T2 ) . 17. Method according to claim 16 that further comprises generating the encoded bit signal (S_e) based on a data bit signal (S_e) , wherein the data bit signal (S_d) represents data to be transmitted. 18. Method according to one of claims 16 or 17 that further comprises detecting a radio-frequency field; - generating, during the pause period (TP) , a reader signal (S_r) based the radio-frequency field; and synchronizing the oscillator signal (S_o) and the reader signal (S_o) during a lock period within the pause period (TP) .
